法規內容.條文內容:
Payments for the expenses of HIV testing, prevention and treatment shall be made to the following:
1. Individuals that have been proved to be infected by HIV (hereafter referred to as the infected), and are reported by medical personnel in accordance with regulations, and meet one of the following qualifications:
(1) Nationals with household registration;
(2) Foreign spouses (including the mainland China, Hong Kong and Macau) infected by national spouses and have appealed and been approved;
(3) Foreign spouses (including the mainland China, Hong Kong and Macau) who have been infected through the course of treatment domestically and have appealed and been approved;
(4) Nationals without household registration that reside legally in the Taiwan Area (hereafter referred to as the nationals without household registration);
(5) Foreign spouses (including the mainland China, Hong Kong and Macau) of nationals holding household registration who reside legally in the Taiwan Area and are pregnant.
2. Individuals who are to accept testing for HIV paid through budget of the central competent authority specified in Article 15 of the Act;
3. Pregnant women who are required of testing for HIV and other necessary measures for the prevention of vertical transmission;
4. Individuals who have experienced occupational exposure to sources of infection and are evaluated by physicians of the designated medical institutions to require testing for HIV infection and treatment for prevention purpose;
5. Infants and children under 18 months of age who are suspected of being infected and are evaluated by physicians of the designated medical institutions to require testing for HIV infection and treatment for prevention purpose;
6. Others that are deemed necessary by the central competent authority to accept testing, prevention or treatment related to HIV.

Expenses that may be applied for payment by medical institutions are as follows:
1. Medical expenses related to the diagnosis and treatment of HIV at outpatient clinics and inpatient hospital care;
2. Expenses of antiretroviral medications;
3. Pharmaceutical service fees for antiretroviral medications;
4. Expenses for the laboratory testing of viral load and CD4 count;
5. Other items designated by the central competent authority.
The payment standards of the expenses mentioned in the preceding Paragraph are as follows:
1. Items and prices for payment decided by the central competent authority;
2. The Fee Schedules for Medical Services of the National Health Insurance;
3. Items and prices of drugs and special materials listed by the National Health Insurance.
For antiretroviral medications regulated in Subparagraph 2 of Paragraph 1, their prescription shall follow the guidelines of the central competent authority.
Designated medical institutions, when applying for expenses of Paragraph 1, shall present the laboratory testing, examination reports and related information of the persons tested or the infected.

Expenses of the following items shall not be paid.  However, this limit is not applicable to hemophilia patients that are infected in the course of medical care.
1. Registration fees, meal expenses, certificate fees, balance billing for wards and other medical costs not related to the treatment of HIV;
2. Items not in accordance with the guidelines for diagnosis and treatment of HIV/AIDS formulated by the central competent authority.

Individuals who meet regulations of Subparagraph 4 of Article 2, their employment organizations (institutions) may apply to the central competent authority for expenses of Subparagraph 2 and Subparagraph 3, Paragraph 1 of Article 5, incurred within the six months period since the occurrence of the incident.
For applications of the preceding Paragraph, the following documents shall be submitted.
1. Original receipts of medical expenses;
2. Detailed list of expenses;
3. Summary of medical records;
4. Statement describing the process of the incident;
5. Report of the needlestick injury and record of follow-up blood testing.
Care providers who meet regulations of Subparagraph 4 of Article 2, in addition to submitting the above-mentioned documents, shall comply with the following regulations differently in regard to whether they are employed by organizations (institutions) or not:
1. Employed by organizations (institutions): submit a copy of Certificate of Care Provider Training, Certificate of Care Provider Technician, or graduation diploma of the relevant discipline.
2. Not employed by organizations (institutions): the employer shall be the only applicant; submit a copy of care provider qualification certificate ( Certificate of Care Provider Training, Certificate of Care Provider Technician, or photocopy of the graduation diploma of the relevant department), a copy of the employment contract, copies of two different forms of photo identifications of the employer, a copy of the cover-page of the deposit account of financial institutions or postal offices owned by the care provider.

Individuals eligible for payment in this set of Regulations, if inspected by the competent authorities to have the following situations, the competent authorities should take appropriate proceedings.
1. Found by designated medical institutions or competent authorities not following medical advice on taking medication or medical treatment;
2. Found by checking the medical care information of the National Health Insurance Administration to have repeated medical care or wasted medical resources.
For the appropriate proceedings mentioned in the preceding Paragraph, the competent authorities may apply the following proceedings in proportion to the severity of the situation:
1. Advise the infected to receive medical care at specific designated medical institutions;
2. Refrain from paying expenses of laboratory testing, prevention and treatment related to HIV in the preceding Paragraph;
3. Suspend temporarily from paying expenses of laboratory testing, prevention and treatment related to HIV.
